  "advert": [
    {
      "description": "\u0026lt;br\u0026gt;\u0026lt;font color\u003d\u0026quot;red\u0026quot;\u0026gt;\u0026lt;strong\u0026gt;\u0026gt;\u0026nbsp;NICE AD (1983)\u0026lt;/strong\u0026gt;\u0026lt;/font\u0026gt;\u0026lt;br\u0026gt;\u0026lt;blockquote\u0026gt;As computing was a serious and professional subject, the humorus adverts was rare in 1983.\u0026lt;br\u0026gt; This one said:\u0026lt;br\u0026gt;\u0026lt;br\u0026gt;\u0026lt;font color\u003d\u0026quot;#666666\u0026quot;\u0026gt; When I told my Dad about NEC TREK, NEC\u0027s new personal computer, he wanted one right away.\u0026lt;br\u0026gt;\u0026lt;br\u0026gt; I told him it has 10 programmable function keys; high powered graphic capabilities, powerful Microsoft BASIC included, and a 8-octave programmable musical tone generator.\u0026lt;br\u0026gt;\u0026lt;br\u0026gt; He said it has lot of \u0027fun games\u0027. \u0026lt;br\u0026gt;\u0026lt;br\u0026gt; I told him how its memory storage can interface with cassette diskette or cartridge, and how it has a wide variety of of sophisticated software available - important things like financial management package...\u0026lt;br\u0026gt;\u0026lt;br\u0026gt; He just challenged me to a game of Protector.\u0026lt;br\u0026gt;\u0026lt;br\u0026gt; That\u0027s my Dad. I love him, but sometimes I wish he could understand how a kid feels.\u0026lt;/font\u0026gt;\u0026lt;/blockquote\u0026gt;",
      "link": "http://www.old-computers.com/museum/adverts/Nec_PC6001_Advert_1.jpg"
    }
  ],
